The tombs are estimated to date from the late 7th century to the mid-9th century, based on the numerous [[:en:Grave goods|Grave goods]] were uncovered from the 29 tombs which were fully [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] in 1987-1988, 1994 to 1998, and 2000. These included shards of [[:en:Haji pottery|Haji]] and [[Sue pottery]], fragments of swords and metal agricultural implements, and thousands of spherical, ''[[magatama]]'' and tubular beads. Of particular interest was a decorated sword hilt discovered in Tomb 15, with a design similar to those made in [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]] on the [[:en:Korea|Korea]] in the late 6th century. Within Tomb 25 a ''[[Wadōkaichin]]'' coin minted in 708 AD was discovered. In 2018, 195 items were collectively designated a National [[:en:Important Cultural Property (Japan)|Important Cultural Property]]<ref name= "Bunka2">{{cite web|url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/442713|title=青森県丹後平古墳群出土品|work=Cultural Heritage Online|publisher=Agency for Cultural Affairs|language=Japanese|accessdate=5 Jun 2022}}</ref> The relics are on display at the Hachinohe City Museum.
